<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-07-17T06:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-07-17T06:44:00-05:00" n="107" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.72/2: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bundy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-17T11:00:00-00:44"><hi rend="italic">July 17,
                                        1920—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received July 18—2:19
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>47. Department’s 32, July 15 [<hi rend="italic">14</hi>], 6 p.m. Act
                            passed by Legislature granting concession to French Cable Company
                            mentioned Legations cable 24, February 27, 1 p.m. was approved by
                            President. Said act appears in the recently published acts of the
                            Legislature passed at its last session. Copies of these published acts
                            were mailed with Legation’s despatch number 83 dated June 23<note n="50" xml:id="d107fn50">Not printed.</note> now <hi rend="italic">en
                                route.</hi></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bundy</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>